ber of students who got that grade\n", "# Example: 38 students got a 0, while 56 students got a 10.\n"], "metadata": {"colab": {"base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"}, "id": "PhHYRh-Zi7OD", "outputId": "8d1d763f-3d50-409d-fb9f-1471a2a1dd0f"}, "execution_count": 26, "outputs": [{"output_type": "stream", "name": "stdout", "text": ["/nFinal grade (G3) distrubution:\n", "G3\n", "0     38\n", "4      1\n", "5      7\n", "6     15\n", "7      9\n", "8     32\n", "9     28\n", "10    56\n", "11    47\n", "12    31\n", "13    31\n", "14    27\n", "15    33\n", "16    16\n", "17     6\n", "18    12\n", "19     5\n", "20     1\n", "Name: count, dtype: int64\n"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "source": ["print(\"/nAverage final grade:\",df['G3'].mean().round(2))\n", "print(\"Lowest Grade:    \",df['G3'].min())\n", "print(\"Highest Grade:   \",df['G3'].max())\n", "#shows average final grade\n", "#were the round(2) limit the decimal values which will be much is easier to read\n"], "metadata": {"colab": {"base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"}, "id": "nF0SLjSGtIVq", "outputId": "cc7956d5-4653-44b7-b9d1-b51e2b40c49a"}, "execution_count": 27, "outputs": [{"output_type": "stream", "name": "stdout", "text": ["/nAverage final grade: 10.42\n", "Lowest Grade:     0\n", "Highest Grade:    20\n"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "source": ["Categorical_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns\n", "print(\"/nCategorical columns:\",list(Categorical_cols))\n", "#print(Categorical_cols)\n", "#shows all categorical columns\n"], "metadata": {"colab": {"base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"}, "id": "wY82JibnughD", "outputId": "9d18e39a-a349-44ee-ef0d-2f0f178599f0"}, "execution_count": 28, "outputs": [{"output_type": "stream", "name": "stdout", "text": ["/nCategorical columns: ['school', 'sex', 'address', 'famsize', 'Pstatus', 'Mjob', 'Fjob', 'reason', 'guardian', 'schoolsup', 'famsup', 'paid', 'activities', 'nursery', 'higher', 'internet', 'romantic']\n"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "source": ["for col in Categorical_cols:\n", "  print(f\"/n{col}: {df[col].unique()}\")\n", "  #shows all unique values in each text column\n", "# f\" stands for 'formatted string,' which lets you put variables directly inside {} brackets.\n"], "metadata": {"colab": {"base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"}, "id": "yGMmbuqLvWS2", "outputId": "a4c2c708-4700-4606-e2b9-78a9e0c7889c"}, "execution_count": 32, "outputs": [{"output_type": "stream", "name": "stdout", "text": ["/nschool: ['GP' 'MS']\n", "/nsex: ['F' 'M']\n", "/naddress: ['U' 'R']\n", "/nfamsize: ['GT3' 'LE3']\n", "/nPstatus: ['A' 'T']\n", "/nMjob: ['at_home' 'health' 'other' 'services' 'teacher']\n", "/nFjob: ['teacher' 'other' 'services' 'health' 'at_home']\n", "/nreason: ['course' 'other' 'home' 'reputation']\n", "/nguardian: ['mother' 'father' 'other']\n", "/nschoolsup: ['yes' 'no']\n", "/nfamsup: ['no' 'yes']\n", "/npaid: ['no' 'yes']\n", "/nactivities: ['no' 'yes']\n", "/nnursery: ['yes' 'no']\n", "/nhigher: ['yes' 'no']\n", "/ninternet: ['no' 'yes']\n", "/nromantic: ['no' 'yes']\n"]}, {"cell_type": "code", "source": ["#corelation with target\n", "print(\"/nCorrelation of each column with G3(final grade):\")\n", "numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include=['number'])# temparory table\n", "print(numeric_df.corr()['G3'].sort_values(ascending=False).round(2))\n"], "metadata": {"colab": {"base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"}, "id": "thRj3YRAxVSU", "outputId": "201f2a91-80a2-44c9-9a5a-95390304e38a"}, "execution_count": 33, "outputs": [{"output_type": "stream", "name": "stdout", "text": ["/nCorrelation of each column with G3(final grade):\n", "G3            1.00\n", "G2            0.90\n", "G1            0.80\n", "Medu          0.22\n", "Fedu          0.15\n", "studytime     0.10\n", "famrel        0.05\n", "absences      0.03\n", "freetime      0.01\n", "Walc         -0.05\n", "Dalc         -0.05\n", "health       -0.06\n", "traveltime   -0.12\n", "goout        -0.13\n", "age          -0.16\n", "failures     -0.36\n", "Name: count, dtype: int64\n"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "metadata": {"id": "939b27f1"}, "source": ["### 🔍 What do these numbers actually mean?\n", "\n", "Think of **correlation** as a way to measure the \\\"friendship\\\" between two things. It tells us how much one column (like study time) moves when another column (like final grades) changes.\n", "\n", "*   **The Scale:** The result is always between **+1.0** and **-1.0**.\n", "*   **Strong Positive (+0.80 to +1.0):** These are like \\\"Best Friends.\\\" For example, **G1** and **G2** have very high numbers, meaning if a student did well in their first tests, they almost always did well in the final grade (**G3**).\n", "*   **Zero (0.0):** No connection at all. A student's **freetime** (0.01) doesn't really tell us anything about what their grade will be.\n", "*   **Negative Numbers (-0.36):** These work like a seesaw. For **failures**, the number is negative. This means as the number of past failures goes **up**, the final grade usually goes **down**.\n", "\n", "**Top Takeaway:** The strongest predictors for a student's final grade in this data are their previous test scores and their mother's education level (**Medu**)."]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "metadata": {"id": "4d814371"}, "source": ["### 🏁 Stage 1 Summary: What Have We Learned?\n", "\n", "We've finished our first look at the data! Here is the 'big picture' of what we found:\n", "\n", "#### 📊 What the outputs told us:\n", "*   **`df.shape`**: We are looking at **395 students** and **33 different details** about their lives.\n", "*   **`df.info()`**: This is our roadmap. We found several text columns (like `Mjob` or `internet`) that we'll eventually need to turn into numbers so the computer can understand them in Stage 3.\n", "*   **`df.describe()`**: We noticed the average grade is about **10.4/20**, but some students have a **0**. This is a big hint that something specific might be causing those low scores.\n", "*   **`df.isnull().sum()`**: Total zeros! This is very rare in the real world—it means our data is perfectly clean and ready to go.\n", "*   **Correlation**: We got a 'sneak peek' at the future. **Previous grades (G1, G2)** and **study time** are the best friends of a high final grade, while **past failures** are its biggest enemy.\n", "\n", "#### 💡 Key Takeaways:\n", "1.  **395 students, 33 features.**\n", "2.  **Target:** `G3` (Final Grade, 0-20).\n", "3.  **Cleanliness:** 100% complete (no missing values).\n", "4.  **The Challenge:** We need to handle the 'text' columns later to make them usable for a Machine Learning model."]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "metadata": {"id": "a4ec0645"}, "source": ["### 📈 Key Performance Indicators (KPIs)\n", "\n", "Based on our initial data exploration, these are the most important 'numbers to watch':\n", "\n", "| KPI | Value | Why it matters |\n", "| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n", "| **Baseline Performance** | 10.42 (Avg Grade) | This is the 'average' student we are trying to predict against. |\n", "| **Predictive Strength** | 0.90 (G2 to G3) | High score means past performance is our strongest tool for prediction. |\n", "| **Academic Friction** | -0.36 (Failures) | Every unit increase in past failures pulls the final grade down significantly. |\n", "| **Intervention Rate** | ~10% (38 zeros) | The percentage of students failing completely who need the most help. |\n", "| **Support Factor** | 0.22 (Medu) | Mother's education is the strongest 'home life' indicator of success in this group. |"]}, {"cell_type": "markdown", "source": [], "metadata": {"id": "6eo60JLe4dVo"}}]}